      "acceptanceCriteria": "N=11 non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs tested; constructs from production lots with documented traceability.",
      "rationale": "Eleven non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs were tested across two independent laboratories. All constructs were sourced from production lots with full dimensional and material traceability. Sample size is consistent with ASTM F1717 requirements and sufficient to characterize construct-to-construct variability."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Multiple test conditions (load levels, displacement rates) evaluated to characterize model response across the COU operating envelope.",
      "rationale": "Testing was performed under a single ASTM F1717 prescribed test condition (quasi-static compression-bending at 5 mm/min). While this condition is clinically representative, only one load configuration was evaluated, limiting coverage of the full operating envelope. Achieved level (2) is below the required level (3) for this factor; this gap is acknowledged and accepted given the standardized nature of the F1717 protocol."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Model input parameters (geometry, material properties, boundary conditions) demonstrably equivalent to test specimen parameters within measurement uncertainty.",
      "rationale": "A formal equivalency assessment compared model inputs to measured specimen parameters. Geometric dimensions agreed within CMM measurement uncertainty (<0.05 mm). Material properties matched coupon test values within one standard deviation. Boundary conditions replicated ASTM F1717 fixture constraints. Equivalency is confirmed."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoI differences <10% for all three quantities; validation metric E/uval < 1.96 for all QoIs.",
      "rationale": "For all three QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm displacement), the ensemble mean FEA predictions differed from experimental means by less than 10%. The validation metric E/uval was below 1.96 for all QoIs, indicating that model-experiment differences are within combined experimental and simulation uncertainty. Acceptance criteria are satisfied."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm displacement) directly relevant to the clinical failure modes and regulatory decision context.",
      "rationale": "The three selected QoIs directly characterize the structural performance attributes most relevant to clinical use: construct stiffness relates to load sharing with the spine, yield force indicates onset of permanent deformation, and force at 40 mm displacement captures post-yield behavior relevant to catastrophic failure. These QoIs are aligned with the regulatory decision context for Class II spinal fixation devices."
    },
